The first approach to solving Next Greater Element I is usually brute force.
For every element, keep searching to the right until a greater element is found.
The solution works, but while implementing it, the number of conditions grows quickly. Nested loops, repeated comparisons, and multiple edge cases make the code harder to maintain.
Instead of adding more conditions, it’s worth understanding the Monotonic Stack pattern.
The Key Observation
Rather than searching to the right for every element, traverse the array from right to left.
This small change makes a huge difference.
The stack stores only the elements that are useful for future comparisons.

• If the current element is smaller than the stack’s top, the top is the next greater element.

• If the current element is larger, keep removing smaller elements from the stack because they can never be the next greater element for any element on the left.

• Finally, push the current element into the stack.
This removes unnecessary comparisons and keeps the logic clean.
Why the Stack Works
The stack is maintained in descending order.
Every time a larger element appears, all smaller elements on the top are removed because they are no longer useful.
Only the important candidates remain in the stack, making every lookup efficient.
Using a Map for Fast Lookup
Once the next greater element for every value in nums2 is found, store it in a Map.
map.set(currentElement, nextGreaterElement);Later, building the answer for nums1 becomes simple.
ans.push(map.get(nums1[i]));No additional searching is required.
JavaScript Solution
nums1 = [1, 3, 5, 2, 4];
nums2 = [6, 5, 4, 3, 2, 1, 7];stack = [];const map = new Map();for (i = nums2.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
if (stack.length == 0) {
stack.push(nums2[i]);
map.set(nums2[i], -1);
} else {
if (nums2[i] < stack[stack.length - 1]) {
map.set(nums2[i], stack[stack.length - 1]);
stack.push(nums2[i]);
} else {
while (
stack.length > 0 &&
nums2[i] > stack[stack.length - 1]
) {
stack.pop();
} if (nums2[i] < stack[stack.length - 1]) {
map.set(nums2[i], stack[stack.length - 1]);
} else {
map.set(nums2[i], -1);
} stack.push(nums2[i]);
}
}
}ans = [];for (i = 0; i < nums1.length; i++) {
ans.push(map.get(nums1[i]));
}console.log(ans);Takeaway
The biggest improvement doesn’t come from memorizing the solution — it comes from understanding why the stack is traversed from right to left, why smaller elements are removed, and why a Map makes the final lookup efficient.
Once these ideas click, the Monotonic Stack pattern becomes much easier to recognize in similar interview problems.
